tweet_text: Today I called for the House to begin an impeachment inquiry into President Trump because there are moments for careful calculation, weighing political expediency & conflicting interests. And there moments for clarity and conviction. This is that moment. https://t.co/5aIv9hQSGZ

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: Read my full statement here: https://t.co/kwtXqsBNzl /12

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: There are moments for careful calculation. For weighing political expediency and conflicting interests. And there moments for clarity and conviction. This is that moment. /11

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: But, I believe an impeachment inquiry will be a fair airing and consideration of the facts that the American people must understand. /10

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: The American people should understand that opening an impeachment inquiry is not removal of the President. Given the behavior of the Senate, that outcome is probably out of the question. /9

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: Unless we restore respect for the law, respect for truth and respect for common decency, we cannot hope to solve any of our other pressing problems. /8

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: But look at where we are today.  Republicans in this chamber cheer or justify or stand woefully silent in the face of behavior for which they would have impeached a Democratic president many times over. Our best and most proven ideas cannot get even a hearing in the Senate. /7

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: Impeachment is divisive. The politics of impeachment are messy and uncertain, and might, in the short run, serve the President’s narrow political interests. /6

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: I have, until now, been conflicted about those interests. Impeachment, along with the right to declare war, is the most awesome power of Congress. /5

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: From the moment of his inauguration, this President has shown contempt for the truth, has attacked our institutions, and has ignored the Constitution he swore to defend. /4

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: But there are moments for calculation. For prudence, compromise and the careful weighing of competing interests. And there are moments for clarity and conviction. This is such a moment. /3

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦

tweet_text: @forkinshirtball @MEPFuller I know Twitter is a universe where logic is not important, but I’m not arguing for doing nothing, I’m arguing for doing what we do in a fully informed way.

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: @pwnedlib @MEPFuller I think you’re not reading it very carefully.

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: @selina3sticks @MEPFuller As a non lawyer, I couldn’t agree more.

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: @MEPFuller There is no explicit duty as there is conduct a census every 10 years. Congress decides if and when to impeach independent of the words of the constitution. That’s not controversial. It’s true. So it’s not unreasonable to try to understand where American sentiment is in deciding.

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: @MEPFuller Lordy. It’s not about a look. Duty is in quotes because the constitution imposes absolutely no obligation to impeach under any circumstance. It’s at the discretion of Congress. Kinda feels like you’re looking for a lot more fireworks than you’re going to find in this quarter.

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: @MEPFuller Like everything else a legislator does, there’s a mix of “knowing” and what public sentiment demands. Especially in the House, where we are called “Representative”. Impeachment could have been granted to SCOTUS, but instead, it was given to the part of our gov closest to people.

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: @MEPFuller I don’t think there’s an opposition between the two in this case. Impeachment is by design a political act, not a judicial or legal one. So public sentiment is as essential (probably more) as any implicit constitutional “duty”.

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: @MEPFuller Anyway, I was making an argument for care and consideration of facts and implications in however we choose to act. I expressed no view on how we should act.

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: @MEPFuller I made the case, because along with the will of my constituents, that would be something I would want to know before developing intense conviction. You know, be as informed as possible before acting?

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: @MEPFuller I don’t know what you heard, but I wasn’t forceful about not impeaching Trump (your words). I was forceful about making sure we had the best picture possible of how impeachment plays in Presidential swing states. Something I don’t know. See the diff?

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: @MEPFuller Which is different than “tamping down” the possibility of impeachment.

name: Jim Himes 🇺🇸🇺🇦
tweet_text: @MEPFuller No it wasn’t. Jim Himes argued that we should reflect on and consider the effect of impeachment proceedings on the chances of the President’s re-election, without prejudice. Because if he is not convicted by the Senate, 2020 is the next mechanism of accountability.
